	urldate = {2021-03-08},
	journal = {MLN},
	author = {Mendoza, Carlos Abreu},
	year = {2017},
	note = {tex.ids= mendozaReadingSimonBolivar2017a
publisher: Johns Hopkins University Press},
	pages = {291--315},
	annote = {Extracted Annotations (5/20/2021, 4:19:31 AM)
"En un pueblecito cercano al Chimborazo se sirvió un banquete a Bolívar ... Los repetidos brindis formaron quizá un diminuto Orinoco ... Bolívar era, por su temperamento, el más eufórico de todos. Y en tal estado de ebriedad patriótica le parecería "muy fácil y sin peligro," la ascensión al Gigante de Nieve. Él, que habitualmente caminaba a paso precipitado, debió subir más aceleradamente que de costumbre, como consecuencia de los repetidos brindis del banquete. Esta leve intoxicación, el mal de las alturas, el Atsma, puna o soroche a que era muy sensible, y la precipitación con que escala el volcán, le causan un desvanecimiento, percance frecuente que sufren los "Neófitos," y hasta los mismos alpinistas. Es entonces, cuando Bolívar se tiende a descansar sobre la roca que desde ese instante se llama "Piedra de Bolívar." Es entonces, durante esta momentánea postración, cuando Bolívar concibe su Delirio, su deslumbrante página literaria, al que le dará forma concreta esa noche, en Riobamba" (Mendoza 2017:301)},
	annote = {Pino Irureta and Enrique Krauze haveunderlined the subtle ways in which Chávez appropriated Bolívar’sfeats and slowly transferred the mythical capital of the Liberator tohis persona. The very title of Krauze’s biography Chávez, El poder y eldelirio (2012), illustrates the connection between the late Venezuelanpresident and Bolívar’s experience at the top of Chimborazo.It is a common place today to underline the strong religiosity thatis embedded in the cult of Bolívar. Historians such as Germán CarreraDamas, Luis Castro Leiva, Yolanda Salas, and the aforementioned PinoIrureta and Krauze have analyzed the most paradigmatic manifesta-tions of a Bolivarian faith that seems to have no limits as it colonizesmost Latin American cultural spheres, even moving beyond the limitsof the continent. The global market of cultural production has seenrecent readings and appropriations of Bolívar’s life and miracles. Twobiographic works published in the last three years by the AmericanTina Datsko de Sánchez and the Peruvian expat Marie Arana attemptto revive Bolívar’s heroism in the context of neoliberal disenchantmentthat calls for a virulent and delirious prophet, a patriarchal messiahwho will fill the void of our lack. Both works perpetuate Bolívar’s cultby reproducing the “three monumental poses”—progress, patriarchalprinciple, and sacred text—that, according to Conway, are the inter-related expressions of its ideology: “a timeless alphabet that may beutilized to respond to ever-changing social and historical realities” (4)
303
 
José Martí also situated Bolívar within the pantheon of LatinAmerican heroes, alongside the political luminaries José de SanMartín and Miguel Hidalgo. In “Tres héroes” (1889) and through aseries of discourses written in honor of Bolívar, the Cuban poet insistson describing Bolívar’s actions within a semantic field rooted in thenatural landscape and linking him, most importantly, to the sublimityof the mountains and height. For Martí, Bolívar has taken hold of thepeoples’ imagination through a series of almost cinematic scenes: wehave seen him unsaddling his horse, hugging San Martín, and cross-ing torrential rivers in places like Carabobo, Guayaquil, and Junín.Among these sacred sites, Chimborazo appears as the place wherewe can witness Bolívar “speaking with immortality” (“La fiesta” 252)and “eternity” (“Discurso” 242). What we find in Martí, as is commonin most of the writings that attempt to describe Bolívar, is a sense ofunboundedness. 1
301
 
The attraction to this solar light of the hero remained strongthroughout the end of the nineteenth century as shown in the worksof the modernistas. Poets like Rubén Darío could not resist the appealof reading Bolívar’s delirium as a providential text that construes aheroic and tireless man, a genius whose glory was materialized andcemented through his ascent to the heights of Chimborazo:Y subiendo la cima del Ande,asomado al fulgor infinito,coronado de luz, lanzó un gritoque resuena doquier: ¡Libertad!
301
 
In his 2003 study of Bolívar’s cult, Elías Pino Irureta points to theimportance of the tropology of light in the Liberator’s receptioninsofar as he undergoes a deification process “debido a que es laencarnación de un mandato de la potestad celestial. El plan políticodel personaje se magnifica debido a la actuación de un designiosobrenatural que lo purifica y diviniza.
300
By unearthing these intricate textual allusions to the messianic tra-dition in “My Delirium” and the Roman Oath, I aim to demonstratetheir influence on subsequent readings of Bolivar’s corpus, specifi-cally on those who took on the role of disseminating the gospel ofhis deeds.
300
 
Grisanti’s account is worth citing extensively:

En un pueblecito cercano al Chimborazo se sirvió un banquete a Bolívar... Los repetidos brindis formaron quizá un diminuto Orinoco ... Bolívarera, por su temperamento, el más eufórico de todos. Y en tal estado deebriedad patriótica le parecería “muy fácil y sin peligro,” la ascensión alGigante de Nieve. Él, que habitualmente caminaba a paso precipitado,debió subir más aceleradamente que de costumbre, como consecuenciade los repetidos brindis del banquete. Esta leve intoxicación, el mal de lasalturas, el Atsma, puna o soroche a que era muy sensible, y la precipitacióncon que escala el volcán, le causan un desvanecimiento, percance frecuenteque sufren los “Neófitos,” y hasta los mismos alpinistas. Es entonces, cuandoBolívar se tiende a descansar sobre la roca que desde ese instante se llama“Piedra de Bolívar.” Es entonces, durante esta momentánea postración,cuando Bolívar concibe su Delirio, su deslumbrante página literaria, al quele dará forma concreta esa noche, en Riobamba ... el 5 de julio de 1822,undécimo aniversario de la Declaratoria de Independencia de Venezuela.Esta coincidencia es el fiat lux que ilumina con meridiana claridad elgénesis del Delirio sobre el Chimborazo. (19)
 

300
 
As underlined by Ronald Briggs, the ten-sion of size between a little hill in Rome and an enormous Americanvolcano shows a narrative of linear progression where “the historicalorder symbolized by ancient Rome would one day be superseded by anAmerican one, the enormous hill in Ecuador will allow Rodríguez themetaphorical space to contemplate this change as it takes place” (45).
297
 
Both the Roman Oath and “My Delirium” as messianic texts arerooted in a biblical tradition of mountains as symbols of and sitefor divine illumination. Throughout the Old and New Testament,God presented Himself to His chosen servants on the mountainsin order to deliver words of truth, clarity, and to commission themfor His divine mission in the world.
296
Mabel Moraña argues, these mountain texts reflect the tensions andnegotiations between “Ilustración y americanismo, occidentalismo ytelurismo, progreso y tradición, creando así las bases híbridas de lasque nace y se afirma el proyecto criollo” (41). 9 For Rotker, these ten-sions were already present in the Roman Oath as a text that projectedAmerica as a futurity: “el lugar de lo posible, de la redención, la tierrade la libertad” (32)
297
 
Since Independence, the interconnected writings of travelers, scien-tists, and poets—both national and foreign—have deployed these awe-inspiring sights as a battlefield for competing scientific, political, andaesthetic agendas that developed throughout the century. 5 Countedamong them, Humboldt, after he failed to climb Chimborazo, left atestimony of the limited scientific usefulness of the ascent by claiming:“these laborious excursions, the narratives of which generally excitethe attention of the public, offer but a very small number of resultsuseful to the progress of science” (238). While acknowledging his fail-ing attempts to reach the summit of Chimborazo, Humboldt’s vividdescription of the sight of the mountain underscores his obsessionwith the visual majesty of the volcano. He writes: “we see Chimbo- [294] razo appear like a cloud at the horizon; it detaches itself from theneighboring summits, and towers over the whole chain of the Andes,like that majestic dome, produced by the genius of Michael Angelo,over the antique monuments, which surround the Capitol” (239). Inother words, once the practical and scientific value of ascending themountain proves to be insufficient, the German naturalist finds acompensatory substitute in its singular aesthetic appeal.
295
 
 
Humboldt’s qualification of the value of nature—as not limited solelyto the scientific but also having aesthetic worth—is achieved withinthe parameters of progress, enlightenment, and secularization. Takentogether, Humboldt and Bolívar propose a productive experience ofnature—one carried out in different stages—but which invariablyconcludes in the poetization of the natural sublime through writing.For nineteenth-century writers, the textualization of the Andean spacerequires an initiation through which the subject constitutes himself inthe discovery of his greatness, thus reproducing a Kantian experienceof the sublime that magnifies human reason over the materiality of theworld. 6
295
 
Usingadjectives such as colossal, majestic, and heavenly, the German explorerinevitably associated the experience of American mountains with thesublime and, therefore, as noted by Mary Louise Pratt, consolidateda view of “a nature that dwarfs humans, commands their being, anddefies their powers of perception” (119–20). Building on Humboldt’sand other non-Latin American precursors by exploiting the rhetoricof an immense and overwhelming national landscape, Bolívar andother foundational figures such as Andrés Bello and Domingo FaustinoSarmiento perpetuated the sublime as the hegemonic lens throughwhich to observe and to write about Latin American nature, includingfrequent depictions of magnificent Andean landscapes such as theEcuadorian Chimborazo. 4
294
 
The deictic, contextual quality of Bolívar’s representations isparticularly timely when considered in the context of the receptionof “My Delirium on Chimborazo” (1822), a controversial text withinBolívar’s production given its possible apocryphal nature. 2 After perus-ing the references, allusions, and artistic depictions of his climb toChimborazo as an allegorical rise to glory, I found that Bolivar’s pub-lics—the poets, historians, and politicians of his time and ours—haveread this text as a kind of scripture, that is, the material revelation ofthe Liberator’s messianic aura.
292},
