	abstract = {The initial thesis of this dissertation concerned a textual imbalance in Nietzsche between Christianity and socialism: By his own assessments Christianity was already historically exhausted and therefore not an appropriate target for attack, whereas socialism, its young successor, was. The hypothesis was that Nietzsche's anti-Christianity was a mask for anti-socialism.    This led directly to an investigation of Nietzsche's politics, a matter traditionally much distorted, minimized, or denied. My studies show that not only is politics the most important aspect of Nietzsche's philosophy, it is the entire philosophy. Nietzsche's philosophy is a political metaphysics. So pervasive is the political (which is dualistic: master and slave), that Nietzsche's attempted monistic ontology--the will to power--was abandoned because incompatible with his metaphysics.    In this perspective, Christianity and socialism become assessable. Nietzsche's relation to Christianity progressively decays from a critical and superior description to a hysterical and vengeful antagonism: Nietzsche's anti-Christianity is a personal and German matter, not a philosophical and European one. In contrast, a progressively increasing concern with socialism, especially in what I identify as his fourth and fifth periods (following the traditional three), is not only European in tone and scope, but is future-looking and therefore justified in a way Christianity could not be. Thus I concluded that socialism is not masked by Christianity, but that nonetheless there is (by traditional assessments) a textual imbalance which is rectified by this systematic analysis.    Nietzsche's future-looking program is also now assessable. That is, the political consolidation of Europe by good Europeans and their domination of the earth for their advantage. However, I find, on morphological grounds, that with the failure of the two German war efforts in the twentieth century, Europe's last opportunity at unification and world leadership is over. Like the Hellenistic imitation of Greece, the world is now Europeanistic, Europe included. However, despite the untimely truncation of Nietzsche's career, I show that he anticipated his philosophy's inadequacy in the tetralogy Zarathustra, announcing its imminent failure in a satyr play.},
