@incollection{sorianoBarber2018,
	address = {Albuquerque},
	title = {Barber},
	isbn = {978-0-8263-5985-8 978-0-8263-5986-5},
	url = {https://ebookcentral.proquest.com/lib/canterbury/detail.action?docID=5528404},
	language = {English},
	urldate = {2022-05-17},
	booktitle = {Tides of {Revolution} {Information}, {Insurgencies}, and the {Crisis} of {Colonial} {Rule} in {Venezuela}},
	publisher = {University of New Mexico Press},
	collaborator = {Soriano, Cristina},
	year = {2018},
	note = {OCLC: 1264422631},
	annote = {- ¿Cuál fue la relevancia histórica de este acontecimiento?
- Involucró a cientos de personas de Caracas y La Guaira
- Se propuso metas más radicales que las del movimiento indepentista triunfante: "establishment of free trade, the abolition of slavery with compensation to slave owners, the elimination of Indian tributes, and the abolition of taxes" y "foster harmony among races: whites, pardos, Indians, and blacks were seen as 'brothers in Jesus Christ.'"
- Obtuvo "remarkable support from many pardos and poor whites, small merchants, royal officials, soldiers, and artisans from La Guaira and Caracas".
- A pesar de que la historia oficial se ha enfocado mucho en los dos criollos que lideraron el movimiento, hubo una participación importante de los líderes pardos: Narciso del Valle y José Cordero, que --al igual que los dos criollos y los dos europeos-- "encouraged people to read and circulate revolutionary texts, recruited people to attend their meetings and discussions, and opened networks of communication with the purpose of articulating a common political plan".

- ¿Qué rol jugaron las tecnologías no-mecánicas de reproducción?
- "created texts that sought to adapt republican ideas to local social and economic circumstances, and through innovative narrative strategies made them accessible to a semiliterate population of color"
- "multimedia sources of information (...) were crucial to the formatio n of an emergent public sphere (...) which escaped the control of elites and colonial authorities, [and] was built not upon printing shops or local newspapers controlled by white creoles but upon effective circuits of reading and sharing manuscripts, stories, and songs among socially diverse participants arranged in their own networks."
- "I argue that the La Guaira movement’s social networks developed around multimedia sources of information that were crucial to the formatio n of an emergent public sphere. This public sphere, which escaped the control of elites and colonial authorities, was built not upon printing shops or local newspapers controlled by white creoles but upon effective circuits of reading and sharing manuscripts, stories, and songs among socially diverse participants arranged in their own networks." Un buen ejemplo de lo anterior es las reuniones en lo de Narciso del Valle, donde según uno de los testimonios se turnaban para leer en voz alta 
- Tener presente que la lectura individual, tan icónica para la mutación cultural propia de la imprenta, no es la norma en estos círculos. De hecho, ahora que lo pienso, esto conecta directamente con lo que propone McLuhan como la característica dominante del mundo pre-Gutenberg. Pero claro, lo interesante aquí es que estamos discutiendo ideas del mundo post-Gutenberg con tecnologías de comunicación que hibridan la lectura individual con la era de los manuscritos.
- New sources, however, showed that for months La Guaira—lacking a printing press or a bookstore—became a center for the exchange of revolutionary information and the production of texts written by Spaniards, white creoles, and pardos who were moved by their own passions, concerns, and political interests.
- Written in a simple narrative and adapted to the circumstances of the province, local manuscripts were far more popular and accessible to readers and listeners of La Guaira than the works of Rousseau and Raynal
- Ella habla en plural de los manuscritos locales, pero los que especifica son los de Picornell, de los que no se conservan sino los comentarios de sus lectores, y que estarían caracterizados por ser “particularly appealing to Venezuelans of African descent, in part because they were written in a style appropriate for reading out loud and making use of catechistic formulas of answers and responses that made reading easier in a context of semiliteracy. They also used familiar and easy-to-memorize narrative formulas such as epistles, dialogues, and stories for more effective oral transmission.” (Soriano, 2018, p. 209)
   - Entre los textos hay dos “cuentecitos”: uno semi-autobiográfico con anagramas de los nombres, y otro sobre José Leonardo Chirinos: ambos aleccionadores a la rebelión y la emancipación; hay por otra parte una “carta” de un abuelo a un nieto, y un "A Dialogue between a Black Lieutenant Colonel of the French Republic and a Black Spaniard" (Soriano, 2018, p. 210)
   - Describe cómo circulaban estos textos: por un lado, facilitaban la lectura en voz alta, que sería una de las formas de transmisión --"in gatherings and tertulias that took place in bodegas and at Valle’s barbershop. Witness testimonies confirm that many visitors and clients read these manuscripts at the barbershop. In fact, Rusiñol, Cordero, and Valle appear as the main agents in charge of spreading these texts through their own social networks. The physician Juan de la Tasa, for example, commented that he had read “the one about Bitatusa, the sermon of the Friar, and another song that a friar from Santo Domingo gave to him." (Soriano, 2018, p. 211)--, y por otra parte "Picornell’s visitors collected these writings, then copied them by hand and distributed them in private homes throughout La Guaira" (Soriano, 2018, p. 211)
   - Una clave: la barbería, que era el lugar de lectura en voz alta y de conspiración, era también un modelo de escuela
   - Otro texto que no conocemos sino por el testimonio de su circulación es uno escrito por Narciso del Valle, para "recruit the black people of Curiepe, exhorting them ‘to unite in order to achieve in this province what the French and the British Americans had done in their countries’”. y sobre “natural equality and the other rights of men.”. Pero Picornell and y Gual, ‘agreed that the letter should be modified because “its style . . . was more elevated than the intelligence of these men, and . . . they should be addressed in a more comprehensible way.’" (Soriano, 2018, p. 212)
   - Los textos que Picornell producía en la cárcel y que se distribuían clandestinamente precedieron la rebelión, y aparentemente también la estimularon. "The complex and diverse group of insurgents also worked closely with him in the elaboration of a political plan, which included the production of a number of documents to organize the rebellion and to map out Venezuela’s first republican government." (Soriano, 2018, p. 212)
   - Buena la declaración al final del capitán general que nombraron después de la rebelión de La Guaira, porque expresa nítidamente la porosidad del Caribe. Esta porosidad es en cierto sentido una de las lecciones que Rodríguez aprende para llevar a la experiencia de los Andes.
},
}

